 presidential election of 1931. He finds that, ultimately, populist mobilization emerged in the country at this time because newly empowered outsiders recognized the limitations of routine political practice and understood how to modify, transpose, invent, and recombine practices in a whole new way. Suggesting striking parallels to the recent populist turn in global politics, Revolutionizing Repertoires offers new insights not only to historians of Peru but also to scholars of historical sociology and comparative politics, and to anyone interested in the social and political origins of populism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aPolitical participationzPeruxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics, PracticalzPeruxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopulismzPeruxHistoryy20th century. 0aPresidentszPeruxElectiony1931. 4aLatin America. 4aPeru. 4acontentious politics. 4ahistorical sociology. 4apolitical innovation. 4apolitical parties. 4apopulism. 4apopulist mobilization. 4apragmatism. 4arepertoires. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226487588423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226487588.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles